  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What's the difference between an appositive and subject compliment?",
  "response": "An **appositive** and a **subject complement** are both grammatical elements that provide additional information about a noun, but they serve different functions in a sentence. Here\u2019s how they differ:\n\n### 1. **Appositive**\n- **Definition**: An appositive is a noun or noun phrase that renames, explains, or clarifies another noun or noun phrase right beside it.\n- **Function**: It provides additional information about the noun it follows or precedes, often in a way that specifies or identifies it more clearly.\n- **Example**:  \n  - \"My friend, **a talented artist**, painted this.\"  \n    Here, \"a talented artist\" is an appositive that renames or describes \"my friend.\"\n- **Position**: It usually appears right next to the noun it modifies, often set off by commas (if nonessential) or without commas (if essential).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Subject Complement**\n- **Definition**: A subject complement is a word or phrase that follows a linking verb (e.g., \"be,\" \"seem,\" \"become\") and describes or renames the subject of the sentence.\n- **Function**: It completes the meaning of the subject by either renaming it (predicate nominative) or describing its state or condition (predicate adjective).\n- **Example**:  \n  - \"She is **a doctor**.\"  \n    Here, \"a doctor\" is a subject complement that renames the subject \"she.\"  \n  - \"The cake smells **delicious**.\"  \n    Here, \"delicious\" is a subject complement that describes the subject \"the cake.\"\n- **Position**: It always follows a linking verb and relates back to the subject.\n\n---\n\n### Key Differences:\n| **Feature**           | **Appositive**                          | **Subject Complement**                  |\n|------------------------|-----------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|\n| **Function**           | Renames or clarifies a noun nearby.     | Describes or renames the subject.       |\n| **Position**           | Adjacent to the noun it modifies.       | Follows a linking verb.                 |\n| **Grammatical Role**   | Acts as a modifier.                     | Completes the subject\u2019s meaning.        |\n| **Example**            | \"My teacher, **Mr. Smith**, is kind.\"   | \"My teacher is **Mr. Smith**.\"          |\n\nIn summary, an appositive directly modifies a noun by renaming or clarifying it, while a subject complement describes or renames the subject through a linking verb.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
